How to Finance the Green Transition
New York — This week, world leaders gathered in New York at the United Nations to assess the global battle against climate change and submit new emission reduction commitments.
The climate crisis is serious, and our pace of action is far too slow.
We are迟迟 unable to shift into high gear.
Accelerating the pace of change requires collaborative efforts from both public and private sectors.
Fortunately, through the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI), private sector collaboration to curb climate change is increasing.
The CFLI was established under the leadership of United Nations Climate Action Envoy Michael Bloomberg, with the aim of mobilizing global private capital to address this critical issue.
This month, the CFLI released a new report, "Financing the Low Carbon Future," outlining how to expand green finance to support a orderly transition to a low-carbon economy, and presenting opportunities for public-private collaboration to achieve the goals of the 2015 Paris Climate Agreement.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects worldwide.
But now, in response to the call by European heads of state and the newly elected President of the European Commission, Ursula von der Leyen, we are ready to show greater ambition and strengthen the EIB's role as a dedicated climate bank within the EU.
The EIB will mainstream climate considerations, target low-carbon investments, and commit at least 1 trillion euros to low-carbon projects over the next decade.
To achieve this goal, by 2025, at least 50% of EIB financing will be directed towards climate action and environmental sustainability.
By the end of 2020, we will align all our financing activities with the goals of the Paris Climate Agreement.
As an important first step, we will exclude energy projects that rely on fossil fuels.
In addition, we will position the EIB as a green finance incubator, committed to mobilizing other resources to help economies transition to a low-carbon future.
As an EU bank, our mission is to invest in Europe's future, and the most important issue of all is climate change.
The more urgent the climate crisis, the stronger our determination.
This summer, European countries experienced record-high temperatures and crop failures due to last year's drought.
Many developing countries have had similar experiences.
Flooding and other climate-related phenomena cost major cities billions of dollars each year, and threaten the lives of even more people.
But the climate crisis is also an opportunity, as financing new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce air pollution that plagues cities around the world.
Shifting investment patterns can accelerate the transition away from fossil fuels. This transition has already begun.
Market forces are increasingly favoring clean energy and moving away from fossil fuels.
In 2011, half of the coal-fired power plants in the United States retired, while the clean energy sector created 3.3 million jobs, compared to less than 100,000 in the coal industry.
In addition, an increasing number of U.S. cities and states have committed to achieving net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will receive support from the Beyond Carbon initiative, which was launched last year by Bloomberg Philanthropies, aiming to support the complete decarbonization of the U.S. economy.
As an international community, we must not only invest in clean energy but also reduce investments in dirty energy.
Currently, in terms of fossil fuel subsidies, we are essentially spending money to promote climate change and air pollution.
These public funds should be used to direct investment toward electric vehicles and other technologies that drive the transformation of the green transition.
These investments will generate significant returns, including reducing the substantial costs of air pollution on public health.
Additionally, we can take numerous measures to direct the necessary capital.
First, we must improve data and disclosure standards.
For a long time, businesses and investors have been unaware of climate-related risks, not knowing the rationale for reducing carbon emissions or protecting assets from extreme weather impacts.
This is beginning to change.
The recommendations of the Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures are guiding companies to allocate capital in more sustainable ways, and also enabling investors to reward those companies that seriously address climate change.
We must also clarify the investment risks associated with green finance.
Cities account for more than 70% of carbon dioxide emissions, but only a few cities in the developing world can obtain credit ratings.
As a result, the total investment in clean public transport, energy-efficient buildings, and other emission-reducing projects has been affected.
Governments and listed banks must increase their efforts to help cities attract capital for these projects, including by participating in initiatives such as the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by the EIB and co-led by Bloomberg Philanthropies.
Third, we need to modernize the grid.
Incentives such as refunds and tax breaks have promoted the expansion of wind and solar power, reducing costs for businesses and consumers.
Now, we should introduce similar programs to accelerate the deployment of battery storage and other emerging technologies to address intermittency issues.
Additionally, better grid connectivity can allow regions with surplus wind and solar power to supply electricity to regions in short supply.
Governments can play a leading role in both areas, encouraging more private investment to flow into clean energy.
Finally, we must continue to expand the green investment market.
In 2007, the EIB issued the world's first green bond on the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, and since then, the green bond market has expanded to $136 billion.
But compared to the $100 trillion global bond market, this is just a drop in the bucket.
Therefore, the EIB is helping the EU develop a classification for sustainable finance standards, so that investors can compare similar projects, just as with standard bonds.
Better and more information about the carbon footprint of investments can enable investors to make informed decisions, thereby driving more private investment into low-carbon projects.
This is how we provide financing for the green transition.
